<org.eclipse.epf.uma:ContentDescription xmi:version="2.0" xmlns:xmi="http://www.omg.org/XMI" xmlns:org.eclipse.epf.uma="http://www.eclipse.org/epf/uma/1.0.6/uma.ecore" xmlns:epf="http://www.eclipse.org/epf" epf:version="1.5.1" xmlns:rmc="http://www.ibm.com/rmc" rmc:version="7.5.1" xmi:id="-rDhhHUZtXpFSrY573Hc3cA" name="new_toolmentor,_C5S8sKLeEd6E3ZvDETLL9g" guid="-rDhhHUZtXpFSrY573Hc3cA" changeDate="2009-11-14T10:46:12.600-0800" version="7.5.0">
  <mainDescription>&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;>&#xD;
    This tool mentor describes how to create &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithUserText&quot; href=&quot;./../../../core.bus.common.extend-ibm/workproducts/functional_area_model_A10F922.html&quot; guid=&quot;_hbPxMHbuEd68WpJEWd56Wg&quot;>Functional Area Model&lt;/a> content using IBM&amp;reg; Rational&amp;reg; Software Architect for WebSphere&amp;reg;&#xD;
    Software, Version 7.5.4 or later.&amp;nbsp; This description assumes that the Rational Software Architect Service Solution&#xD;
    Design Model (the SoaML) template is being used.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;>&#xD;
    In the template, create the Functional Area Model content under the Functional Areas Description package.&amp;nbsp; The&#xD;
    location of this package can be seen, for example, in &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot; href=&quot;./../../../practice.tech.soma.service_identification.base-ibm/guidances/toolmentors/rsa_create_candidate_services_source_elements_F0F4FA20.html&quot; guid=&quot;_-SzssJpsEd6o74-wQ-l20w&quot;>Tool Mentor: Create Candidate Services Source Elements&lt;/a>&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;>&#xD;
    &lt;strong>&lt;font size=&quot;3&quot;>Create domains, functional areas, and business service interfaces&lt;/font>&lt;/strong>&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;div style=&quot;MARGIN-RIGHT: 0px&quot;>&#xD;
            Create a new Business Domain/Functional Area structure in the model using the&#xD;
            &lt;code>&amp;lt;&amp;lt;BusinessDomain&amp;gt;&amp;gt;&lt;/code> building block that can be found in the model template's&#xD;
            &lt;code>&amp;lt;&amp;lt;modelLibrary&amp;gt;&amp;gt;&lt;/code> Service Design Building Blocks package.&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
        &lt;/div>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;div style=&quot;MARGIN-RIGHT: 0px&quot;>&#xD;
            Create additional Functional Areas under the Business Domain by using the &lt;code>&amp;lt;&amp;lt;Functional&#xD;
            Area&amp;gt;&amp;gt;&lt;/code> sub-block that is under the &lt;code>&amp;lt;&amp;lt;BusinessDomain&amp;gt;&amp;gt;&lt;/code> block.&amp;nbsp; Copy&#xD;
            the portion of the model that begins with the &lt;code>&amp;lt;&amp;lt;Functional Area&amp;gt;&amp;gt;&lt;/code> component, and paste&#xD;
            that under the appropriate &lt;code>&amp;lt;&amp;lt;BusinessDomain&amp;gt;&amp;gt;&lt;/code>.&#xD;
        &lt;/div>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;div style=&quot;MARGIN-RIGHT: 0px&quot;>&#xD;
            For each collection of cohesive business functions that you will assign to a&amp;nbsp;Functional Area, create a new&#xD;
            &lt;code>&amp;lt;&amp;lt;BusinessService&amp;gt;&amp;gt;&lt;/code> interface&amp;nbsp;under the BusinessServices package in the model&#xD;
            template.&amp;nbsp; Populate this Interface with the appropriate operations.&#xD;
        &lt;/div>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p style=&quot;MARGIN-RIGHT: 0px&quot;>&#xD;
    &lt;strong>&lt;font size=&quot;3&quot;>Assign&amp;nbsp;interfaces to functional areas&lt;/font>&lt;/strong>&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p style=&quot;MARGIN-RIGHT: 0px&quot;>&#xD;
    Functional areas provide or require business services.&amp;nbsp; These can be modeled using, for example, SoaML &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithUserText&quot; href=&quot;./../../../core.tech.common.extend_supp_soa-ibm/guidances/concepts/service_point_soaml_E250D92A.html&quot; guid=&quot;_9jRdMFbAEd6MCpkuB85p5g&quot;>ServicePoints&lt;/a>,&amp;nbsp;&lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithUserText&quot; href=&quot;./../../../core.tech.common.extend_supp_soa-ibm/guidances/concepts/request_point_soaml_DD83CF2.html&quot; guid=&quot;_5DYKcFbAEd6MCpkuB85p5g&quot;>RequestPoints&lt;/a>,&amp;nbsp;and &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithUserText&quot; href=&quot;./../../../core.tech.common.extend_supp_soa-ibm/guidances/concepts/service_interface_soaml_CA95983A.html&quot; guid=&quot;_N5e2oFbBEd6MCpkuB85p5g&quot;>ServiceInterfaces&lt;/a> -- service-oriented modeling techniques can be used for business&#xD;
    modeling, as well as for IT service modeling.&amp;nbsp; Approaches for doing this are described in the tool mentors that&#xD;
    accompany the Service Specification practice.&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p style=&quot;MARGIN-RIGHT: 0px&quot;>&#xD;
    Conventional modeling of the Functional Area components and their&amp;nbsp;interfaces can be performed as follows:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;div style=&quot;MARGIN-RIGHT: 0px&quot;>&#xD;
            Create&amp;nbsp;UML Ports by selecting the Functional Area component, right-clicking, and&amp;nbsp;selecting&#xD;
            &lt;strong>Add UML &amp;gt; Port&lt;/strong>.&amp;nbsp; Create a Port&amp;nbsp;for each of the following:&#xD;
        &lt;/div>&#xD;
        &lt;ol>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                &lt;div style=&quot;MARGIN-RIGHT: 0px&quot;>&#xD;
                    Each BusinessService that the Functional Area provides&#xD;
                &lt;/div>&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                &lt;div style=&quot;MARGIN-RIGHT: 0px&quot;>&#xD;
                    Each BusinessService that the Functional Area requires&#xD;
                &lt;/div>&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
        &lt;/ol>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;div style=&quot;MARGIN-RIGHT: 0px&quot;>&#xD;
            Upon Port creation, a dialog opens that provides the opportunity to type the Port with either a Class or an&#xD;
            Interface&#xD;
        &lt;/div>&#xD;
        &lt;ol>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                &lt;div style=&quot;MARGIN-RIGHT: 0px&quot;>&#xD;
                    If you know the Port will support only a provided interface, and this will be involved only in simple&#xD;
                    request-response communication, type the Port with the appropriate BusinessService interface.&#xD;
                &lt;/div>&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                &lt;div style=&quot;MARGIN-RIGHT: 0px&quot;>&#xD;
                    Otherwise, type the Port with a Class.&amp;nbsp; It is fine to type the Port with a new Class that is&#xD;
                    created &quot;on the fly&quot; by the tooling.&amp;nbsp; If you do this, you most likely will&amp;nbsp;need to rename the&#xD;
                    Class and the Port so that the names are more meaningful.&#xD;
                &lt;/div>&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
        &lt;/ol>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;div style=&quot;MARGIN-RIGHT: 0px&quot;>&#xD;
            You need to assign BusinessService interfaces to the Ports you typed with Classes. Do this as follows:&#xD;
        &lt;/div>&#xD;
        &lt;ol>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                &lt;div style=&quot;MARGIN-RIGHT: 0px&quot;>&#xD;
                    Select the Port, then select its Properties view&#xD;
                &lt;/div>&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                &lt;div style=&quot;MARGIN-RIGHT: 0px&quot;>&#xD;
                    Using the Interfaces tab of the Properties view, assign provided and/or required interfaces.&#xD;
                &lt;/div>&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
        &lt;/ol>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p style=&quot;MARGIN-RIGHT: 0px&quot;>&#xD;
    Each Functional Area building block begins with two Ports, which you can use or delete as you desire.&amp;nbsp; To type one&#xD;
    of these Ports, select the Port, then use the &lt;strong>Select Type&lt;/strong> button on the &lt;strong>General&lt;/strong> tab&#xD;
    of its Properties view to set its type.&amp;nbsp; Rename the Port appropriately.&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
